Building an Understanding of How Nodes in Neural Networks Work¶

Gary Lawson - 19 May 2019¶

1.0 Abstract¶

This project focuses on using Python and Keras to build and compare a series of dense, convolutional, and recurrent neural network models of varying configurations to accomplish the natural language processing (NLP) tasks of predicting Reuters article news categories. Several experimental designs were conducted to evaluate model structures and hyperparameters to provide insight into what factors impact model accuracy. Through these experiments, all three network structures were found to be able to predict news categories with accuracies greater than 0.930. One dimensional convolutional neural network proved to be the most accurate with comparatively minimal training times while recurrent neural networks were found to be extremely resource intensive to achieve equal validation accuracies to other models.

2.0 Introduction¶

The intent of this exercise is to begin to experiment with recurrent neural networks (RNNs) and compare the results to dense and convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for time series data. Using a reduced Reuters corpus of news articles and their respective news categories, this project will aim to achieve the following goals: 1) Explore dense versus RNN model structures and results. 2) Explore one-dimensional CNNs versus RNN model structures and results. 3) Explore long short-term memory (LSTM) model architectures. 4) Achieve a firm understanding of how neural networks can accomplish NLP tasks.

3.0 Literature Review¶

For coding examples, a thorough understanding of how RNNs work, and tips on how to tune hyperparameters within a RNN, Chollet (2018) and associated code examples were extremely helpful. I further strengthened my understanding of RNNs, specifically the LSTM and gated recurrent unit (GRU) after reviewing Buduma’s (2015) blog post and the Skymind article. The tutorial by Brownlee (2017) was terrific in breaking down embeddings and conceptualizing how they are created in for use in neural nets. Géron’s textbook (2017) was also helpful in building knowledge around the architectures of RNNs, LSTMs, and GRUs. Last, jumpstart code provided as part of this assignment, as well as code authored by Dr. Thomas Miller in previous courses was used to import and process the text data into embeddings.

4.0 Methods¶

As an initial step in model design and analysis is exploratory data analysis (EDA). In this step, it is important to review the data to get an understanding of what it consists of, as well as preparing it for use in the neural networks. Methods to accomplish this include looking at the number of observations (rows) and features (columns). The dataset used will be a reduced Reuters corpus created to include only news articles with one associated category. To create this reduced corpus, jumpstart code will be used to import the full Reuters dataset from Keras, reduced to the one-category articles, and saved as a json file for later use. Keras tools will then be used to tokenize the text words into vectors. Both pre-trained and learned word embeddings will be used in this project.

In Experiments #1, the intent is to first build a simple fully connected neural network that will learn word embeddings from the training data. This dense network will contain one hidden layer and vary several hyperparameters such as the number of nodes (16, 32, 64) and the hidden layer activation function (sigmoid, tanh, ReLU). The optimization function was not evaluated, as past experience has suggested the rmsprop optimization has been successful. Experiment #2 will be similar but will instead use pre-trained word embeddings in the model. For the purpose of this experiment, all other parameters will be held constant. A loop will be used to iterate through every combination of targeted hyperparameters using Keras, with each iteration being considered a specific model. All models evaluated in this project will be trained on ten epochs and will use an embedding dimension of 50. Comparison tables of all models will include the time to train the model and the accuracy based on the training and validation sets.

Similar to the experiments discussed previously, Experiments #3 will be used to compare how a simple RNN performs. Due to the differing concept of nodes in RNNs, hidden layer activations were not evaluated in this experiment, however the number of nodes (16, 32, and 64) were consistent with previous experiments for comparison purposes. Additionally, several different optimizers (SDG, Adam, AdaGrad, RMSProp) were tested to see how they impact the learning of an RNN. Experiments #4 compares the performance and results from LSTM and GRU architectures to the basic RNN model. No iterations will be done on these models, as the optimal hyperparameters from the basic RNN model will be used. Experiments #5 #6, and #7 will take the model architecture from Experiment #4 with the best performance and will explore the impacts of dropout, multi-layered, and bidirectional RNNs. For dropout rates, two loops will be used to iterate through combinations of 0.1, 0.3, and 0.5 for both the dropout and recurrent dropout rates.

The focus of Experiment #8 is to develop 1-dimensional CNN model to compare to the performance of the RNN models developed previously. Additionally, an experiment will be performed to combine a CNN and RNN model to see if a performance increase or training time decrease is experienced.

def sizeof_fmt(num, suffix='B'):
    for unit in ['','Ki','Mi','Gi','Ti','Pi','Ei','Zi']:
        if abs(num) < 1024.0:
            return "%3.1f%s%s" % (num, unit, suffix)
        num /= 1024.0
    return "%.1f%s%s" % (num, 'Yi', suffix)

#import json  
#import zipfile

def zip_open_file(zip_loc, file_name, var_name): 
    with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_loc, "r") as z:
        for line in open(file_name, 'r'):
            var_name.append(json.loads(line))

embeddings_index = {}
def parse_word_embed(filename, var_name):
    f = open(embeddings_filename_50d, encoding="utf8")
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs
    f.close()

    print('Found %s word vectors.' %len(embeddings_index))

# Define a function to plot Model Accuracy and Model Loss

def plot_figs(model_id, model_type, mod_nodes):
    # Create plot figure
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,3))
    
    # Calculate accuracy and loss variables
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    
    epochs = range(1, len(acc)+1)
    
    # Plot training and validation accuracy
    plt.subplot(1,2,1) # Subplot #1
    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Model Accuracy for Model No. %r,\n Model Type %r, \nNo. of Nodes: %r'\
          %(model_id, model_type, mod_nodes)) 
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    
    # Plot training and validation loss
    plt.subplot(1,2,2) # Subplot #1
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Model Loss for Model No. %r,\n Model Type %r, \nNo. of Nodes: %r'\
          %(model_id, model_type, mod_nodes)) 
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')

# Create a loop to iterate through model variations
for nodes in mod_nodes:
    for hid_act in hidden_activation:
        
        # Print the basic parameters of the model being iterated
        print('---------------------------------------------------------------')    
        print("Model No.: %r" %model_id)
        print("Model Type: %r" %model_type)
        print("Number of Layers: %r" %mod_layers)
        print("Number of Nodes: %r" %nodes)
        print("Hidden Layer Activiation: %r" %hid_act)
        print("Hidden Layer Optimizer: %r" %optimizer)

        # Set seeds for reproducible results
        seed(1)
        set_random_seed(2)
        rn.seed(3)
            
        # Define the model structure that is to be evaluated.
        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Embedding(max_words, embedding_dim, input_length=900))

        model.add(Dense(32, activation=hid_act))

In [182]:
# Create a loop to iterate through model variations
for nodes in mod_nodes:
    for hid_act in hidden_activation:
        
        # Print the basic parameters of the model being iterated
        print('---------------------------------------------------------------')    
        print("Model No.: %r" %model_id)
        print("Model Type: %r" %model_type)
        print("Number of Layers: %r" %mod_layers)
        print("Number of Nodes: %r" %nodes)
        print("Hidden Layer Activiation: %r" %hid_act)
        print("Hidden Layer Optimizer: %r" %optimizer)
        
        start_time = time.clock() # start timer to evaluate how long it takes to train this base model

        # Set seeds for reproducible results
        seed(1)
        set_random_seed(2)
        rn.seed(3)

        # Define the model structure that is to be evaluated.
        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Embedding(max_words, embedding_dim, input_length=900))
        model.add(Flatten())
        model.add(Dense(32, activation=hid_act))
        model.add(Dense(9, activation=out_activation))
        #print(model.summary())
        
        model.layers[0].set_weights([embedding_matrix])
        model.layers[0].trainable = False

        model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                      loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                      metrics=['acc'])

        history = model.fit(train_data, train_labels,
                            epochs=mod_epochs,
                            batch_size=mod_batch_size,
                            validation_data=(test_data, test_labels))

        #model.save_weights('pre_trained_glove_model.h5')

        # Stop the timer and append time to list
        end_time = time.clock() # end timer
        runtime = end_time - start_time  # seconds of wall-clock time 
        print("\nProcessing time (seconds): %f" % runtime)  # print process time to train model        
        processing_time.append(runtime) # append process time results to list for comparison table

        # Identify and print maximum accuracy and epoch where that accuracy was realized
        epoch_max = np.argmax(history.history['acc'])
        acc_max = max(history.history['acc'])
        print('Maxium Accuarcy: %r, Epochs Required to Achieve this Accuracy: %r' %(acc_max, epoch_max))

        # Print validation accuracy
        val_acc_max = max(history.history['val_acc'])
        print("Validation Accuracy: %r" %val_acc_max) 
        
        # Plot the accuracy and loss of each model iteration
        plot_figs(model_id, model_type, nodes)

        # Append lists with values for this model ID
        model_id_list.append(model_id)
        model_type_list.append(model_type)
        embedding_dim_list.append(embedding_dim)
        article_len_list.append(article_len)
        n_layer_list.append(mod_layers)
        node_list.append(nodes)
        hidden_activation_list.append(hid_act)
        out_activation_list.append(out_activation)
        optimizer_list.append(optimizer)
        max_acc_list.append(acc_max)
        valid_perform_list.append(val_acc_max)
        epoch_max_list.append(epoch_max)
        batch_size_list.append(mod_batch_size)

        model_id += 1

In [262]:
# Create a loop to iterate through model variations
for nodes in mod_nodes:
    for opt in optimizer:


        # Print the basic parameters of the model being iterated
        print('---------------------------------------------------------------')    
        print("Model No.: %r" %model_id)
        print("Model Type: %r" %model_type)
        print("Number of Layers: %r" %mod_layers)
        print("Number of Nodes: %r" %nodes)
        print("Hidden Layer Optimizer: %r" %opt)

        start_time = time.clock() # start timer to evaluate how long it takes to train this base model

        # Set seeds for reproducible results
        seed(1)
        set_random_seed(2)
        rn.seed(3)

        # Define the model structure that is to be evaluated.
        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Embedding(input_dim=max_words, 
                            output_dim=nodes))
        model.add(SimpleRNN(nodes))
        model.add(Dense(9, activation=out_activation))
        #print(model.summary())

        model.compile(optimizer=opt,
                      loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                      metrics=['acc'])

        history = model.fit(train_data, train_labels,
                            epochs=mod_epochs,
                            batch_size=mod_batch_size,
                            validation_data=(test_data, test_labels))

        #model.save_weights('pre_trained_glove_model.h5')

        # Stop the timer and append time to list
        end_time = time.clock() # end timer
        runtime = end_time - start_time  # seconds of wall-clock time 
        print("\nProcessing time (seconds): %f" % runtime)  # print process time to train model        
        processing_time.append(runtime) # append process time results to list for comparison table

        # Identify and print maximum accuracy and epoch where that accuracy was realized
        epoch_max = np.argmax(history.history['acc'])
        acc_max = max(history.history['acc'])
        print('Maxium Accuarcy: %r, Epochs Required to Achieve this Accuracy: %r' %(acc_max, epoch_max))

        # Print validation accuracy
        val_acc_max = max(history.history['val_acc'])
        print("Validation Accuracy: %r" %val_acc_max) 

        # Plot the accuracy and loss of each model iteration
        plot_figs(model_id, model_type, nodes)

        # Append lists with values for this model ID
        model_id_list.append(model_id)
        model_type_list.append(model_type)
        embedding_dim_list.append(embedding_dim)
        article_len_list.append(article_len)
        n_layer_list.append(mod_layers)
        node_list.append(nodes)
        out_activation_list.append(out_activation)
        optimizer_list.append(opt)
        max_acc_list.append(acc_max)
        valid_perform_list.append(val_acc_max)
        epoch_max_list.append(epoch_max)
        batch_size_list.append(mod_batch_size)

        model_id += 1

# Print the basic parameters of the model being iterated
print('---------------------------------------------------------------')    
print("Model No.: %r" %model_id)
print("Model Type: %r" %model_type)
print("Number of Layers: %r" %mod_layers)
print("Layer Type: %r" %layer_type)
print("Number of Nodes: %r" %mod_nodes)
print("Hidden Layer Optimizer: %r" %optimizer)

start_time = time.clock() # start timer to evaluate how long it takes to train this base model

# Set seeds for reproducible results
seed(1)
set_random_seed(2)
rn.seed(3)

# Define the model structure that is to be evaluated.
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(input_dim=max_words, 
                    output_dim=mod_nodes))
model.add(LSTM(mod_nodes, return_sequences=True))
model.add(LSTM(mod_nodes*2))
model.add(Dense(9, activation=out_activation))
#print(model.summary())

model.compile(optimizer=optimizer,
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['acc'])

history = model.fit(train_data, train_labels,
                    epochs=mod_epochs,
                    batch_size=mod_batch_size,
                    validation_data=(test_data, test_labels))

#model.save_weights('pre_trained_glove_model.h5')

# Stop the timer and append time to list
end_time = time.clock() # end timer
runtime = end_time - start_time  # seconds of wall-clock time 
print("\nProcessing time (seconds): %f" % runtime)  # print process time to train model        
processing_time.append(runtime) # append process time results to list for comparison table

# Identify and print maximum accuracy and epoch where that accuracy was realized
epoch_max = np.argmax(history.history['acc'])
acc_max = max(history.history['acc'])
print('Maxium Accuarcy: %r, Epochs Required to Achieve this Accuracy: %r' %(acc_max, epoch_max))

# Print validation accuracy
val_acc_max = max(history.history['val_acc'])
print("Validation Accuracy: %r" %val_acc_max)

plot_figs(model_id, model_type, mod_nodes)

embedding_dim_list.append(embedding_dim)
article_len_list.append(article_len)
n_layer_list.append(mod_layers)
layer_type_list.append(layer_type)
node_list.append(mod_nodes)
out_activation_list.append(out_activation)
optimizer_list.append(optimizer)
max_acc_list.append(acc_max)
valid_perform_list.append(val_acc_max)
epoch_max_list.append(epoch_max)
batch_size_list.append(mod_batch_size)

model_id += 1

5.0 Results¶

The dataset used for this experiment included 5,583 training articles and 2,208 test articles. The max article length was approximately 900 words, so the training and test tensors were set to have a length of 900 vectors. There were nine categories including trade, ship, acq, earn, money-fx, interest, crude, and money-supply. The data was processed to include only the top 10,000 words, which were tokenized and converted into sequence vectors for use in creating embeddings.

Experiment #1 evaluated different combinations of nodes and activation functions in a basic dense network. The results of this experiment are included in Table 1. This simple dense neural network performed surprisingly well with validation accuracies ranging from 0.934 to 0.943. Training accuracies reached 0.998, suggesting overfitting. It was found that all model combinations performed comparably, indicating the number of nodes and activation function may not be play a large role in the accuracy of an NLP problem. All models trained fairly quickly at around 18 seconds. Figure 1 shows an example of the accuracy and loss curves for Model No. 9 (Tanh activation and rmsprop optimizer), suggesting the model was quick to train over just a few epochs, and then begins to overfit as training accuracies continue to increase while validation accuracies level off, and validation loss no longer improves. Experiment #2 resulted in disappointing results, as training and validation accuracies in a model that used a 50-dimensional pre-trained embedding dimension were 0.501 and 0.490. The results of this experiment are included in Table 2 and an example of the accuracy and loss curve is included in Figure 2.

Experiment #3 used two loops to iterate through the number of nodes and several optimizers in a RNN model that used learned word embeddings. The results shown in Table 3 suggest that a simple RNN can be used to predict news article classes with accuracies reaching 0.841. The models with larger numbers of nodes and the RMSProp and Adam optimizers performed the best, with SDG and AdaGrad being quite inferior in performance and training time. Figure 3 shows that significant overfitting is occurring in the model with 64 nodes and the RMSProp optimizer, as training accuracies continue to increase over each epoch while validation accuracy levels off and even drops a bit. The loss graphic in Figure 3 also suggests overfitting with validation loss hitting a minimum and then beginning to increase after approximately 4 epochs. The training time of an RNN is significantly higher than dense networks at approximately 500 seconds.

Experiment #4 compared the basic RNN of the previous example to an LSTM and GRU models, holding all other hyperparameters constant. When compared to the top basic RNN accuracy of 0.841, Table 4 shows the improvement in validation accuracy with both the LSTM and GRU models was substantial, coming in at 0.928 and 0.922 respectively. The cost to achieve these accuracies was training time, as the LSTM and GRU models took approximately 4.4 and 3.4 times longer to train, respectively. Comparing the LSTM and GRU models directly indicates that for approximately the same accuracy, the GRU model trains at about 30% faster. Figures 4 and 5 show the accuracy and loss curves for the LSTM and GRU models, respectively.

While inefficient from a training standpoint, the LSTM network was use for Experiments #5 through #7 to test different configurations of the RNN structure. Table 5 shows the results from including dropout and recurrent dropout in the model, and it can be seen that it does in fact help prevent the model from overfitting. This is shown by the relatively similar training and validation accuracies, as well as a slight improvement in overall generalization on the validation data with a configuration of a 0.3 dropout rate and a 0.1 recurrent dropout rate. Including dropout also increased the training time over the standard LSTM model by approximately 10%. The accuracy and loss curves are included as Figure 6. Experiment #6 considered a multi-layered LSTM model. The results of this experiment are shown in Table 6, and reveal a slight loss in validation accuracy, suggesting information loss may have been experienced by adding additional layers. The accuracy and loss curves for this model are shown in Figure 7. The results of Experiment # 7 which focused on creating a bidirectional LSTM model are included in Table 7. This model was able to slightly outperform the base LSTM model by about 1% but was approximately 107% slower to train. Accuracy and loss curves for this model are included as Figure 8.

The last experiment created a 1-dimensional CNN model to compare to the RNN models trained previously. Additionally, a combination of a LSTM and CNN were developed. Table 8 shows that a 1-dimensional CNN outperforms all RNN models developed, resulting in an accuracy 1.5% higher than any RNN and training in a fraction of the time at approximately 29 seconds. While slightly less accurate than the CNN alone and slower to train, the combination model outperformed all other RNN models in terms of both validation accuracy and training time. The accuracy and loss curves of these two models are shown in Figures 9 and 10.

If the previous experiments were created to help develop a strategy for creating a chatbot to assist customer service representatives, Table 9 is a summary to provide insight in finding the best model to do this. To accomplish the task of NLP in the bot, dense, RNN, and CNN models all showed the ability to achieve accuracies greater than 0.930 with the CNN model proving to be the best all-around model in terms of accuracy and training time. RNNs proved to be the most resource intensive with comparatively large training times. In a production environment, RNNs may not be cost effective seeing as other models could achieve slightly better accuracy at a fraction of the training time. If an RNN structure is selected for an NLP task, the GRU could offer the best compromise of accuracy and training time. Additional hyperparameters added to the RNN model such as dropout, additional layers, and bidirectional layers improve accuracy slightly, but the resulting training times are significantly increased. A large amount of training data specific to the problem proved to be the best option for creating embeddings, as pre-trained embeddings did not perform better than random.
